    explanation: "A hold harmless clause (also called a release or exculpatory clause) is a contractual provision where one party agrees not to hold the other party responsible for certain damages, losses, or liabilities. It's closely related to indemnification but has a slightly different focus — while indemnification requires active compensation, hold harmless prevents the claim from being made in the first place.\n\nHold harmless clauses come in three forms: broad form (one party assumes all liability, even for the other's negligence), intermediate form (one party assumes liability except for the other's sole negligence), and limited form (each party is responsible for their own negligence).\n\nCourts scrutinize hold harmless clauses carefully, especially those that attempt to release a party from liability for their own negligence. Many jurisdictions have anti-indemnity statutes that limit the enforceability of broad form hold harmless clauses, particularly in construction contracts.",
